HEADWORD: Dimity
<hw>Dim"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr. Gr. <?/ of
double thread, dimity; <grk>di-</grk> = <grk>di`s-</grk> twice + <?/ a
thread of the warp; prob. through D. <ets>diemet</ets>, of F.
<ets>dimite</ets>, <ets>d⟦eacute⟧mitte</ets>. Cf.
<er>Samite</er>.]</ety> <def>A cotton fabric employed for hangings and
furniture coverings, and formerly used for women's under-garments. It is
of many patterns, both plain and twilled, and occasionally is printed in
colors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

